{"title_page": "Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir\n|native_name =\n|image = Buddhagosa mahasthavir.jpg\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Sapta Ratna Vajracharya\n|alias =\n|dharma name = Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir\n|birth_date = 12 October 1921\n|birth_place = Kwa Baha, [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|death_date = {{d-da|24 September 2011|12 October 1921}}\n|death_place = \n|nationality = Nepalese\n|religion = [[Buddhism]]\n|school = [[Theravada]]\n|lineage = \n|title = \n|location =\n|education = \n|occupation = [[Bhikkhu|Buddhist monk]]\n|ordination = [[Mandalay]], [[Burma]]\n|teacher = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|students = \n|website = \n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n'''Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u092c\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0918\u094b\u0937 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0935\u093f\u0930, born '''Sapta Ratna Vajracharya''', 12 October 1921&nbsp;\u2013 24 September 2011) was a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive [[Theravada Buddhism]] in [[Nepal]] in the 1940s in the face of suppression by the [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] regime.\n\nHe was the founder of Pariyatti Shiksha (Buddhist education) in the country, and in 2006 was named the fifth Sangha Nayaka (Chief Prelate).<ref name=\"ekantipur\">{{cite news|last=Vajracharya|first=Suwarn|title=Bhante Buddhaghosa|url=http://www.ekantipur.com/the-kathmandu-post/2011/11/05/oped/bhante-buddhaghosa/227888.html|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=The Kathmandu Post|publisher= |date=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Kondanya2011\">{{cite news|last=Kondanya|first=Bhikshu|title=Bhikshu Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir|url= |accessdate=|newspaper=The Dharmakirti|publisher= |date=12 October 2011}} Pages 7-9.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSapta Ratna was born to father Purnananda and mother Surjamaya Vajracharya in Kwa Baha, [[Kathmandu]]. In 1940, he went to [[Kushinagar]], India, and was ordained as a novice monk. He was given the dharma name Buddhaghosa. He then went to [[Burma]], where he studied Buddhism and meditation, and in 1943 received higher ordination as a full monk in [[Mandalay]]. He was the first from a [[Vajracharya]] family to become a Theravada monk.<ref name=\"ekantipur\" />\n\n==Dharma work==\nReturning to Nepal, Buddhaghosa (alternative names: Bhante Buddhaghosa, Buddhaghosa Mahathero) lived at the monastery of Sumangal Vihar in [[Lalitpur District, Nepal|Lalitpur]] and dedicated himself to spreading the Buddha's message.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url= http://www.theravadanepal.net/vihar/ptn/sumangalvihar.php|title= Sumangal Vihar|publisher= Theravada Nepal|accessdate= 4 June 2012|year= 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite news|last=Kloppenborg|first=Ria|title=Theravada Buddhism in Nepal|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_05_04_03.pdf|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=Kailash|publisher= |date=}} Page 305.</ref> The 1940s were bad times for Buddhist monks, and a number of them had been expelled for preaching and producing Buddhist literature.<ref>LeVine, Sarah and Gellner, David N. (2005). ''Rebuilding Buddhism: The Theravada Movement in Twentieth-Century Nepal.'' Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|9780674019089}}. Page 48.</ref>\n\nAfter the fall of the Rana regime and establishment of democracy in Nepal in 1951,<ref>Brown, T. Louise (1996). ''The Challenge to Democracy in Nepal: A Political History.'' Routledge. {{ISBN|0415085764}}, 9780415085762. Page 21.</ref> Theravada Buddhist monks could preach freely. In 1963, Buddhaghosa started Pariyatti Shiksha and revolutionized Buddhist education by teaching it in a scientific manner.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://anandakutivihar.com.np/pariyatti.html |title= Pariyatti |publisher=Ananda Kuti Vihar|accessdate=4 June 2012|year= 2011}}</ref> The weekly dharma classes attracted large numbers of youths, and the study of Buddhism progressed beyond sermons and services.<ref name=\"ekantipur\" /><ref name=\"Kondanya2011\" />\n\nBuddhaghosa authored, translated, or edited 22 books in [[Nepal Bhasa]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]] on the [[Tripitaka]], which consists of the Theravada Buddhist scriptures.\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1999, Buddhaghosa was decorated with the title of Aggamahasaddhammajotikadhaja (light of supreme teaching) by the government of [[Myanmar]] for his contribution to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Kondanya2011\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theravadanepal.net/Biography/Buddhagosha.php |title= AggaMahaSaddhammaJothikadhaja SanghaNayaka Most Venerable Bhikkhu Buddhagosha Mahathero |publisher= Theravada Nepal |accessdate= 4 June 2012 |year= 2011 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Modern Buddhist writers}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahasthavir, Buddhaghosa}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kathmandu]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhism in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Newar]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhism writers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male writers]]\n[[Category:Nepal Bhasa writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir\n|native_name =\n|image = Buddhagosa mahasthavir.jpg\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Sapta Ratna Vajracharya\n|alias =\n|dharma name = Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir\n|birth_date = 12 October 1921\n|birth_place = Kwa Baha, [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|death_date = {{d-da|24 September 2011|12 October 1921}}\n|death_place = \n|nationality = Nepalese\n|religion = [[Buddhism]]\n|school = [[Theravada]]\n|lineage = \n|title = \n|location =\n|education = \n|occupation = [[Bhikkhu|Buddhist monk]]\n|ordination = [[Mandalay]], [[Burma]]\n|teacher = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|students = \n|website = \n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n'''Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u092c\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0918\u094b\u0937 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0935\u093f\u0930, born '''Sapta Ratna Vajracharya''', 12 October 1921&nbsp;\u2013 24 September 2011) was a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive [[Theravada Buddhism]] in [[Nepal]] in the 1940s in the face of suppression by the [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] regime.\n\nHe was the founder of Pariyatti Shiksha (Buddhist education) in the country, and in 2006 was named the fifth Sangha Nayaka (Chief Prelate).<ref name=\"ekantipur\">{{cite news|last=Vajracharya|first=Suwarn|title=Bhante Buddhaghosa|url=http://www.ekantipur.com/the-kathmandu-post/2011/11/05/oped/bhante-buddhaghosa/227888.html|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=The Kathmandu Post|publisher= |date=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Kondanya2011\">{{cite news|last=Kondanya|first=Bhikshu|title=Bhikshu Buddhaghosa Mahasthavir|url= |accessdate=|newspaper=The Dharmakirti|publisher= |date=12 October 2011}} Pages 7-9.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSapta Ratna was born to father Purnananda and mother Surjamaya Vajracharya in Kwa Baha, [[Kathmandu]]. In 1940, he went to [[Kushinagar]], India, and was ordained as a novice monk. He was given the dharma name Buddhaghosa. He then went to [[Burma]], where he studied Buddhism and meditation, and in 1943 received higher ordination as a full monk in [[Mandalay]]. He was the first from a [[Vajracharya]] family to become a Theravada monk.<ref name=\"ekantipur\" />\n\n==Dharma work==\nReturning to Nepal, Buddhaghosa (alternative names: Bhante Buddhaghosa, Buddhaghosa Mahathero) lived at the monastery of Sumangal Vihar in [[Lalitpur District, Nepal|Lalitpur]] and dedicated himself to spreading the Buddha's message.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url= http://www.theravadanepal.net/vihar/ptn/sumangalvihar.php|title= Sumangal Vihar|publisher= Theravada Nepal|accessdate= 4 June 2012|year= 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*{{cite news|last=Kloppenborg|first=Ria|title=Theravada Buddhism in Nepal|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_05_04_03.pdf|accessdate=3 June 2012|newspaper=Kailash|publisher= |date=}} Page 305.</ref> The 1940s were bad times for Buddhist monks, and a number of them had been expelled for preaching and producing Buddhist literature.<ref>LeVine, Sarah and Gellner, David N. (2005). ''Rebuilding Buddhism: The Theravada Movement in Twentieth-Century Nepal.'' Harvard University Press. {{ISBN|9780674019089}}. Page 48.</ref>\n\nAfter the fall of the Rana regime and establishment of democracy in Nepal in 1951,<ref>Brown, T. Louise (1996). ''The Challenge to Democracy in Nepal: A Political History.'' Routledge. {{ISBN|0415085764}}, 9780415085762. Page 21.</ref> Theravada Buddhist monks could preach freely. In 1963, Buddhaghosa started Pariyatti Shiksha and revolutionized Buddhist education by teaching it in a scientific manner.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://anandakutivihar.com.np/pariyatti.html |title= Pariyatti |publisher=Ananda Kuti Vihar|accessdate=4 June 2012|year= 2011}}</ref> The weekly dharma classes attracted large numbers of youths, and the study of Buddhism progressed beyond sermons and services.<ref name=\"ekantipur\" /><ref name=\"Kondanya2011\" />\n\nBuddhaghosa authored, translated, or edited 22 books in [[Nepal Bhasa]] and [[Nepali language|Nepali]] on the [[Tripitaka]], which consists of the Theravada Buddhist scriptures.\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1999, Buddhaghosa was decorated with the title of Aggamahasaddhammajotikadhaja (light of supreme teaching) by the government of [[Myanmar]] for his contribution to Buddhism.<ref name=\"Kondanya2011\" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theravadanepal.net/Biography/Buddhagosha.php |title= AggaMahaSaddhammaJothikadhaja SanghaNayaka Most Venerable Bhikkhu Buddhagosha Mahathero |publisher= Theravada Nepal |accessdate= 4 June 2012 |year= 2011 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Modern Buddhist writers}}\n\n{